title: For Sale/Trade:  Matching WWI British Lee Enfield SMLE MK III*Rifle
postcontent: For sale or trade for a Glock, 26, 43, 19, AR-15 or what do you have.Honest example of a World War I British Lee-Enfield SMLE MK III* rifle, chambered for .303. It is in VG+ condition considering it is 102 years old, matching, and in good working order. It comes with its original magazine The SMLE MK III 1916 was the standard issue rifle throughout the British army when the war began in 1914. While its large magazine, fast operating bolt, short and handy size, charger loading, and good ergonomics made it well suited for trench warfare; it was a bit too expensive and time consuming to produce in the numbers needed at the time. So in 1915, the MK III* pattern was accepted as a wartime economy. Really not much changed, except unnecessary features like the magazine feed cut off and volley sights were removed. Later, the windage knob on the rear sight would also go away, and late in the war the cocking piece would be simplified. Just little things like that but the rifles remained every bit as reliable, durable, and accurate as ever. My sell price is $700.00 will not last long, they do not come up for sale very often, Sale or Trade, looking for Pistol .No low ballers.

title: For Sale:  M91/30 Mosin Nagant PU Sniper
postcontent: Have for sale a 1943 Tula PU Sniper. Rifle is in overall great shape, few typical dings and scratches you find on old surplus rifles. Rifle's serial numbers match, except for magazine plate which is forced matched, scope mount and scope are missmatched. Rifle has the correct Tula factory markings for sniper use, but likely lost it's original scope during the refurbishment process. It shoots very accurately but the mount needs adjusting, currently if I place the scope at around 300 yards it will shoot dead on at 100 yards, easy fix but I need money for an upcoming move so decided to sell it instead. The scope itself is potentially one of the oldest in the USA, it was produced at the No. 3 Kharkov plant in 1940, No. 3 Kharkov was the plant that originally started the PU scope production, they only made roughly 5500 scopes in 1940, this one is No. 4460, meaning it was also originally intended for an SVT 40 but placed on a 91/30 at some point down the line. Scope optics are clear and scope itself is in great shape. Will include scope cover, scope caps, attached sling and Mosin cleaning kit.Willing to drive a reasonable distance from Reading. Please no trades, I'm prepairing to move west and I could use the extra money for hotels and gas. If you don't like my price, make me an offer, all reasonable offers will be considered.
